To use a local variable as a procedure name in a Callproc statement, you should assign the name of the procedure to that variable during the execution and use that local variable in the Callproc Statement. For example:
```4GL
local procname;
if (condition) then
   set procname = 'your_procedure_name';
end if;
callproc procname();
```

The `procname` parameter specifies the name of the procedure you are calling in the Callproc statement. You can use an actual procedure name or a variable that resolves to a procedure name at runtime. If you use an actual procedure name, OpenROAD resolves the reference at compile time. For example: `callproc myProcedure()`.

If you use a variable to represent the procedure name so that the user can specify a procedure at runtime, for example:
```4gl
dim myProcName as char;
myProcName = "myProcedure";
callproc myProcName();
```
In this case, OpenROAD resolves the reference at runtime.

You can pass values by reference to a 4GL procedure in Actian 4GL using the `byref(variable)` option in the Callproc statement. Here is an example:
```4GL
local value1 = 5;
callproc myProcedure(parameter1 = byref(value1));
// In the called procedure, you can modify value1
print value1; // Output: 6 (If the procedure doubled the input value)
```

To call an external FORTRAN procedure from a method of a user class in OpenROAD, follow these steps:
1. Define the method containing the Callproc statement. For example:
```
method callFortranProcedure;
  declare i as integer;
  callproc myfortranProcedure(i);
end;
```
2. Implement the FORTRAN procedure. Make sure it's compiled and linked to your OpenROAD application. The prototype for the external function should resemble: `external subroutine myfortranProcedure(i as integer)`.
3. Call the method from a frame or another procedure whenever needed. For example:
```
frame mainFrame;
  declare obj as myUserClassType;
  open obj using "my_user_class";
  call obj.callFortranProcedure(5);
end;
```
4. In the FORTRAN procedure, accept an integer value from the Callproc statement and manipulate or process it according to your requirements.

When you use an actual procedure name, OpenROAD resolves the reference at compile time and the procedure call is hard-coded into your application. On the other hand, when you use a variable to represent the procedure name, OpenROAD resolves the procedure reference at runtime based on the value of the variable. For example, using an actual procedure name: `callproc MyProcedure();`. This call will always refer to the "MyProcedure" procedure. However, if you want to change the called procedure based on some condition or user input, use a variable:
```sql
set procedureName to 'UserSelectedProcedure';
callproc procedureName();
```
In this example, `procedureName` is a variable that could be set to any valid procedure name during runtime. When the Callproc Statement is executed, it will call the procedure corresponding to the value of `procedureName`.
